value.value: any structural anomaly of the second cranial nerve which is responsible for conveying visual information from the retina to the brain; it extends from the retina to the optic chiasma where part of its fibers become the optic tract and cross to the opposite side and pass to the geniculate bodies
misprojection or aberrant target finding of the second cranial nerve which is responsible for conveying visual information from the retina to the brain
absence of the second cranial nerve which is responsible for conveying visual information from the retina to the brain

absence of the band of the paired bands of optic nerve fibers running from the optic chiasma mostly to the lateral geniculate body, with a smaller number of fibers terminating in the superior colliculus and the pretectal region
absence of natural or normal moisture in the eye
any structural anomaly of the skin folds covering the front of the eyeball
missing skin folds covering the front of the eyeball when closed
strongly protruding eyelids
ptosis, drooping eyelids

acquired diminution of the size of the sebaceous glands embedded in the tarsal plate of each eyelid, associated with wasting as from death and reabsorbtion of cells, diminished cellular proliferation, decreased cellular volume, pressure, ischemia, malnutrition, reduced function or malfunction, or hormonal changes
any structural anomaly of the glands that secrete tears
missing the glands that secrete tears
any functional anomaly of the glands that secrete tears

an unusually high amount of fluid in the eye, either oversecreted by the lacrimal glands, or due to imperfect drainage by the tear conducting passages, often resulting in overflow of fluid from the eye onto the cheek
when compared to controls, subjects exhibit greater than the normal level of domineering, assaultive posture and/or hostile physical action toward other mice

no domineering, assault posture nor hostile physical action toward male mice

a domineering, assault posture and/or hostile physical action toward inanimate objects
altered behavior of animals to approach and examine other animals
reclusive behavior; the tendency to refrain from participating in social situations and to seek isolation

definition.value: In mice, one sign of this phenotype is that animals will remain physically distant, and do not sleep in piles with cagemates.

value.value: altered emotional response related to anticipation of a non-specific threat
when compared to controls, subjects exhibit more responses thought to be indicative of anxiety in behavioral tests
when compared to controls, subjects exhibit fewer responses thought to be indicative of anxiety in behavioral tests

any change from the common preference of an initiating organism to initiate sexual contact with a receptive partner; in rodents, this usually refers to males that attempts to initiate sexual behavior with males and females indiscriminately
deviation from the normal cycle or inability of females to respond favorably to males that initiate sexual behavior
increased, reduced or absent attempt of sexual behavioral contact between an initiating organism and a receptive partner
anomalies in the ability to propulse semen from the genital ducts and the urethra to the exterior
altered ability to achieve a rigid state of the penis obtained in the condition in which the erectile tissue is filled with blood
males do not as frequently initiate sexual behavior (as scored by the presence of copulation plugs in rodents, not due to infertility)

any anomaly in the ability of a nesting female to retrieve stray pups to the nest or a delay in retrieving stray pups
the killing and eating of newborn mice by the mother; however, this can be a normal response if the mother does not recognize the pups as her own
anomaly in the behaviors related to a female tending to young
altered ability or inability to change body posture or shift a body part
deviation from the normal motility of the visual organs
a change from the normal manner of moving the tail
altered ability or inability to move from place to place in response to stimuli
inability to coordinate voluntary muscular movements

circling behavior exhibited in both clockwise and counterclockwise directions
circling behavior in one direction only, either clockwise or counterclockwise
general restlessness or excessive movement; more frequent movement from one place to another or having an increased state of activity
increased reaction to touch
marked by fitful, jerky movements
general reduced locomotor activity; reduced movement from one place to another or having a decreased state of activity
failure of neonates or embryos to initiate any voluntary or spontaneous change in position or posture, with or without external stimulus
reduced ability to execute integrated movements of muscle
abnormal pattern of movement of the limbs of animals, characterized by elements of progression, stability, speed and length over the ground
